---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="Mealie fork"
  path="/projects/mealie/"
  description="A fork of Mealie, the self-hosted recipe manager, that I build, deploy, and extend for a nutrition-tracking pipeline. Plus an upstream fix for poisoned schema.org data."
  lede="A fork of Mealie, the self-hosted recipe manager (12.7k stars upstream), that I build, deploy, and extend for a nutrition-tracking pipeline. I ship the images, run them in the homelab, and send the generic fixes back upstream."
  tags={['CI/CD', 'Docker', 'GHCR', 'Python', 'Vue', 'Open source']}
  demonstrates="CI/CD surgery, Docker and GHCR pipelines, Python and Vue across the full stack, upstream open-source contribution, and the discipline of running what you build."
  links={[
    { label: 'Upstream PR #7881', href: 'https://github.com/mealie-recipes/mealie/pull/7881' },
  ]}
>
  <h2>Why it exists</h2>
  <p>
    I'm moving roughly 300 recipes off a commercial app with two structural
    problems. Its search indexes the title and nothing else, so searching
    "Worcestershire" returns zero results for the recipes that call for it. And
    there is no nutrition field anywhere in its data model, which makes the one
    thing I actually want impossible rather than merely missing. Mealie has
    both.
  </p>
  <p>
    Same model as my Android fork: own the code so "I wish it had X" becomes
    something you just do.
  </p>

  <h2>The CI that went green and built nothing</h2>
  <p>
    Upstream's pipeline is built for upstream, and none of it works on a fork.
    Four separate things had to be fixed, but only the first one was dangerous:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>The publish job was gated to the upstream repo.</strong>
      <code>if: github.repository == 'mealie-recipes/mealie'</code>. On a fork
      that condition is false, so the job is skipped, the run reports
      <strong>green</strong>, and no image is ever built. A pipeline that fails
      loudly costs you ten minutes. One that succeeds while doing nothing costs
      you however long it takes to notice.
    </li>
    <li>
      It built through a paid build service I have no token for. Swapped for
      stock buildx with layer caching.
    </li>
    <li>
      It pushed to the maintainer's registry namespace. Permission denied on a
      fork, so I publish to my own instead.
    </li>
    <li>
      The registry rejects uppercase image names, and my username has capitals
      in it. The repo name gets lowercased explicitly. I also dropped a second
      architecture that was doubling build time for hardware I don't run.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    A related trap worth naming: the CLI in that repo defaults to the
    <em>parent</em>, not the fork. Every command has to be pointed at the fork
    explicitly or you're reading upstream's CI and concluding your build never
    ran. That one cost real time.
  </p>

  <h2>What I built</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Nightly images to my own registry,</strong> built by the repaired
      pipeline above and deployed to the homelab through Portainer.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Backend.</strong> Added nutrition to the recipe list schema with a
      batched eager-load instead of an N+1 query.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Frontend.</strong> A full editorial redesign: image-forward tiles,
      a real typographic hierarchy, colored taxonomy tags, dark and light. The
      root cause of "it looks dated" turned out to be one file: the theme plugin
      set colors but never component defaults, so every card, button and chip in
      the app rendered stock Material regardless of palette. Adding defaults
      there restyled every page with a small, rebase-safe diff.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>One-tap filing.</strong> Recipes file into cookbooks from the card
      itself. It has one genuinely dangerous edge, demonstrated below.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Upstream fix (PR #7881).</strong> The recipe yield display emitted
      "0.0" into the schema.org JSON-LD for servings-only recipes, poisoning
      per-serving data for anything that consumed it. I fixed it and added
      parametrized tests. (Demonstrated below.)
    </li>
  </ul>


  <h2>The upstream bug, PR #7881</h2>
  <p>
    Mealie emits schema.org JSON-LD for every recipe, which is how any consumer
    (search engines, scrapers, nutrition trackers) reads it. The yield string was
    built from the yield <em>quantity</em> and the yield <em>text</em>, and a
    validator coerces an unset quantity to zero. So a recipe with servings but no
    explicit yield emitted a bare <code>"0.0"</code>. Not missing. Zero.
  </p>
  <p>
    That number is the denominator for anything per-serving. Flip between the
    builds and watch what a consumer computes.
  </p>

  <div class="jsonld-demo bleed" data-jsonld>
    <div class="map-controls">
      <span class="ctl-label">build</span>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-fix="before" aria-pressed="true">before #7881</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-fix="after" aria-pressed="false">after #7881</button>
      <span class="sep"></span>
      <span class="ctl-label">yield</span>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-ytype="servings" aria-pressed="true">servings only</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-ytype="text" aria-pressed="false">quantity + text</button>
    </div>

    <div class="map-controls" data-servings-wrap>
      <label class="ctl-label" for="servings">count</label>
      <input id="servings" type="range" data-servings min="1" max="12" step="1" value="4" />
      <output class="ctl-out" data-servings-out>4</output>
    </div>

    <pre class="code-out" data-json aria-label="emitted schema.org JSON-LD"></pre>
    <div class="consumer" data-consumer aria-live="polite"></div>

    <p class="sample-note">
      Switch to a quantity-and-text yield and it degrades from destructive to
      merely wrong: <code>"8.0 slices"</code> instead of <code>"8 slices"</code>.
      That's why it survived. The visible case looked like a cosmetic trailing
      zero, and the case that actually poisoned the math only fired for
      servings-only recipes, in emitted metadata nobody reads by eye. The fix
      handles both (fall back to servings; format the number so whole numbers
      lose the <code>.0</code>) and ships with parametrized tests over every
      yield shape.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Why recoloring it never worked</h2>
  <p>
    Two rounds of theme work went in and it still looked dated. I was moving
    information around and adjusting a palette, and neither touches the thing
    that was actually wrong: the theme plugin set <em>colors</em> and never set
    <em>component defaults</em>, so every card, button and chip in the app kept
    rendering stock Material underneath whatever palette I gave it. Elevation
    shadows, 4px radii, filled chips. You cannot recolor your way out of a
    shape problem.
  </p>
  <p>
    Adding defaults in that one file restyled every page in the app: recipes,
    search, cookbooks, meal planner, settings. Small diff, rebase-safe, because
    upstream barely touches it.
  </p>

  <div class="ui-demo bleed" data-ui>
    <div class="map-controls">
      <span class="ctl-label">recipe card</span>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-ui-mode="stock" aria-pressed="true">stock Material</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-ui-mode="editorial" aria-pressed="false">after the redesign</button>
    </div>

    <div class="ui-stage stock" data-ui-stage>
      <article class="rcard">
        <div class="rcard-photo"></div>
        <div class="rcard-body">
          <h3 class="rcard-title">Sausages in Blanket</h3>
          <ul class="rcard-tags">
            <li>Dinner</li>
            <li>Quickies</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="rcard-meta"><b>208</b> kcal · 4 servings</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>

    <p class="sample-note" data-ui-note aria-live="polite"></p>
  </div>

  <h2>The share bug that was the whole point</h2>
  <p>
    The reason this migration exists: I track macros in MacroFactor, and the
    workflow is share a recipe from Mealie, import it there. On the old app that
    auto-filled. From my fork it came up empty every time, so the migration was
    dead until it worked.
  </p>
  <p>
    The share call passed three things: a title, a URL, and a text field that
    happened to be the same string as the title. On iOS, <code>navigator.share</code>
    maps to a system activity sheet, where the URL arrives as one item type and
    the text as another. With both present, the receiving app picks. MacroFactor
    took the string and ignored the URL, so its import field sat blank.
  </p>
  <p>
    The fix was deleting one redundant field. That's it. The failure looked like
    a broken integration and was actually a platform detail about how two
    attachment types compete inside a share sheet. It imports now.
  </p>

  <h2>The fix that broke production</h2>
  <p>
    Worth showing because it went wrong. A code review flagged an N+1: I'd put
    nutrition on the base recipe summary, so meal plans and shopping lists,
    which nest that summary, lazy-loaded nutrition per row. The clean fix was a
    fork-only subclass carrying nutrition, used only by the recipe list.
  </p>
  <p>
    It deployed and the calories vanished from every card. The list route still
    declared the base class as its response model, and the framework coerces
    each item to the declared type, dropping fields it doesn't know about. The
    data was fine. The serialization silently ate it.
  </p>
  <p>
    I reverted to the approach I'd already verified (nutrition on the summary,
    with a batched eager-load) and accepted the N+1 as a known issue. At ten
    recipes it costs about thirty milliseconds, and I'd rather carry a measured,
    documented cost than chase it with a second refactor I can't verify without
    another deploy. Being right about the N+1 didn't make the fix right.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>The discipline</h2>
    <p>
      Upstream the generic, fork-carry the opinionated. Generic fixes go
      upstream so they're maintained forever at no cost to me. Opinionated
      features stay small and rebasable, so pulling in upstream changes never
      turns into a merge fight.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>The one that could quietly destroy his library</h2>
  <p>
    Tapping the pill on a card files the recipe into a cookbook. Recipes are
    multi-membership on purpose: one can live in Dinner and DELICIOUS and
    Quickies at once. The trap is that the patch endpoint <strong>replaces</strong>
    the category list with exactly what you send it.
  </p>
  <p>
    So the obvious implementation, send the category the user just tapped, is
    catastrophic and completely silent. Tap a category below and watch the
    shelf.
  </p>

  <div class="wipe-demo bleed" data-wipe>
    <div class="map-controls">
      <span class="ctl-label">a toggle sends</span>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-mode="naive" aria-pressed="true">just the tapped category</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-mode="additive" aria-pressed="false">read, merge, send all</button>
      <span class="sep"></span>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-reset>reset the recipe</button>
    </div>

    <div class="wipe-grid">
      <div>
        <div class="rcard">
          <div class="rcard-photo">
            <span class="rcard-cat"><i class="dot"></i><span data-pill>Dinner</span><i class="caret">▾</i></span>
            <span class="rcard-kcal">412 kcal</span>
          </div>
          <div class="rcard-body">
            <h3 class="rcard-title">Cheeseburger Baked Potato Boats</h3>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="menu">
          <p class="menu-head">file into…</p>
          <ul class="menu-list" data-menu></ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <p class="possess-label">cookbooks this recipe is actually in</p>
        <ul class="shelf" data-shelf></ul>
        <pre class="code-out" data-wire aria-label="the PATCH request this toggle sends"></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="wipe-damage" data-damage></p>

    <p class="sample-note">
      His real cookbook set, minus one whose name I am not putting on a
      portfolio. The read-modify-write is the whole fix and it is four lines,
      which is exactly why it is the kind of thing that ships wrong: the naive
      version works perfectly on any recipe that is only in one folder, and
      every test you would write by hand starts with a recipe in one folder.
      Verified on the wire before I trusted it: toggling DELICIOUS onto a recipe
      already in Dinner has to come back <code>[Dinner, DELICIOUS]</code>, not
      <code>[DELICIOUS]</code>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <script is:inline src="/js/mealie-demo.js" defer></script>
  <script is:inline src="/js/wipe-demo.js" defer></script>
</ProjectLayout>
